  "footnotes": [
    "Lusatian culture (c.1300–500 BCE): one of the most significant late Bronze Age cultures in Central Europe, centered in modern Poland; its people built fortified settlements including Biskupin (a remarkably preserved lake village in Greater Poland, often called 'Polish Pompeii'); the culture's ethnic identity remains debated — possibly proto-Slavic, proto-Germanic, or pre-Indo-European",
    "Baptism of Poland (966): Mieszko I's adoption of Latin Christianity from Bohemia (rather than from the German Empire) was a strategic masterstroke — it gave Poland direct ties to Rome, legitimized the Piast state internationally, and helped resist German missionary-cum-political expansion; the date marks the conventional beginning of Polish statehood",
    "Battle of Grunwald / Tannenberg (1410): the Polish-Lithuanian-allied army under Władysław II Jagiełło decisively defeated the Teutonic Knights; it was one of the largest medieval battles in Europe (~60,000 combatants); the victory broke the Order's power and is considered a defining moment of Polish and Lithuanian national identity",
    "Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth (1569–1795): the 'Republic of Both Nations' was unique in Europe for its elected monarchy, powerful parliament (Sejm), and extensive noble rights (Golden Liberty); at its peak it was the largest state in Europe; the liberum veto (any single deputy could block legislation) eventually paralyzed governance and enabled foreign manipulation",
    "Constitution of 3 May 1791: the second codified national constitution in the world (after the US Constitution); it abolished the liberum veto, established separation of powers, and enfranchised townspeople; it provoked Russian and Prussian invasion — the constitution was in force for only 14 months before the Second Partition",
    "Partitions of Poland (1772–1795): Russia, Prussia, and Austria dismembered the Commonwealth in three stages, erasing Poland from the map for 123 years; Polish national identity survived through language, Catholicism, literature (Mickiewicz · Chopin), and repeated uprisings (1794 · 1830 · 1863)",
    "Solidarity (1980): the independent trade union founded at the Gdańsk Shipyard was the first free labor union in the Soviet bloc; with 10 million members, it became a mass social movement; its Round Table negotiations (1989) led to semi-free elections that triggered the fall of communism across Eastern Europe"
  ]
